Seminormed space of formula_8-th power integrable functions

Each set of functions formula_93 forms a vector space when addition and scalar multiplication are defined pointwise. 
That the sum of two formula_8-th power integrable functions formula_94 and formula_102 is again formula_8-th power integrable follows from formula_150 
although it is also a consequence of &quot;Minkowski&#x27;s inequality&quot; 
formula_151 
which establishes that formula_152 satisfies the triangle inequality for formula_153 (the triangle inequality does not hold for formula_154). 
That formula_93 is closed under scalar multiplication is due to formula_152 being absolutely homogeneous, which means that formula_157 for every scalar formula_158 and every function formula_159 

Absolute homogeneity, the triangle inequality, and non-negativity are the defining properties of a seminorm. 
Thus formula_152 is a seminorm and the set formula_93 of formula_8-th power integrable functions together with the function formula_152 defines a seminormed vector space. In general, the seminorm formula_152 is not a norm because there might exist measurable functions formula_94 that satisfy formula_118 but are not equal to formula_117 (formula_152 is a norm if and only if no such formula_94 exists). 

