The Lebesgue formula_11 space

The normed vector space formula_232 is called or the of formula_8-th power integrable functions and it is a Banach space for every formula_153 (meaning that it is a complete metric space, a result that is sometimes called the Riesz–Fischer theorem). 
When the underlying measure space formula_95 is understood then formula_222 is often abbreviated formula_237 or even just formula_238 
Depending on the author, the subscript notation formula_239 might denote either formula_222 or formula_241 

If the seminorm formula_152 on formula_93 happens to be a norm (which happens if and only if formula_244) then the normed space formula_245 will be linearly isometrically isomorphic to the normed quotient space formula_232 via the canonical map formula_247 (since formula_248); in other words, they will be, up to a linear isometry, the same normed space and so they may both be called &quot;formula_11 space&quot;.

The above definitions generalize to Bochner spaces. 

In general, this process cannot be reversed: there is no consistent way to define a &quot;canonical&quot; representative of each coset of formula_250 in formula_238 For formula_252 however, there is a theory of lifts enabling such recovery.

===Special cases===
For formula_153 the formula_40 spaces are a special case of formula_11 spaces; when formula_95 are the natural numbers formula_257 and formula_258 is the counting measure. More generally, if one considers any set formula_95 with the counting measure, the resulting formula_11 space is denoted formula_261 For example, formula_262 is the space of all sequences indexed by the integers, and when defining the formula_8-norm on such a space, one sums over all the integers. The space formula_264 where formula_2 is the set with formula_2 elements, is formula_3 with its formula_8-norm as defined above. 

Similar to formula_269 spaces, formula_270 is the only Hilbert space among formula_11 spaces. In the complex case, the inner product on formula_270 is defined by
formula_273
Functions in formula_270 are sometimes called square-integrable functions, quadratically integrable functions or square-summable functions, but sometimes these terms are reserved for functions that are square-integrable in some other sense, such as in the sense of a Riemann integral .

As any Hilbert space, every space formula_270 is linearly isometric to a suitable formula_276 where the cardinality of the set formula_61 is the cardinality of an arbitrary basis for this particular formula_278 

If we use complex-valued functions, the space formula_18 is a commutative C*-algebra with pointwise multiplication and conjugation. For many measure spaces, including all sigma-finite ones, it is in fact a commutative von Neumann algebra. An element of formula_18 defines a bounded operator on any formula_11 space by multiplication.

===When ===

If formula_282 then formula_283 can be defined as above, that is:
formula_284
In this case, however, the formula_8-norm formula_286 does not satisfy the triangle inequality and defines only a quasi-norm. The inequality formula_287 valid for formula_288 implies that
formula_289
and so the function
formula_290
is a metric on formula_291 The resulting metric space is complete.

In this setting formula_11 satisfies a &quot;reverse Minkowski inequality&quot;, that is for formula_293
formula_294

This result may be used to prove Clarkson&#x27;s inequalities, which are in turn used to establish the uniform convexity of the spaces formula_11 for formula_296 .

The space formula_11 for formula_154 is an F-space: it admits a complete translation-invariant metric with respect to which the vector space operations are continuous. It is the prototypical example of an F-space that, for most reasonable measure spaces, is not locally convex: in formula_40 or formula_300 every open convex set containing the formula_117 function is unbounded for the formula_8-quasi-norm; therefore, the formula_117 vector does not possess a fundamental system of convex neighborhoods. Specifically, this is true if the measure space formula_95 contains an infinite family of disjoint measurable sets of finite positive measure.

The only nonempty convex open set in formula_305 is the entire space. Consequently, there are no nonzero continuous linear functionals on formula_306 the continuous dual space is the zero space. In the case of the counting measure on the natural numbers (i.e. formula_307), the bounded linear functionals on formula_40 are exactly those that are bounded on formula_309, i.e., those given by sequences in formula_310 Although formula_40 does contain non-trivial convex open sets, it fails to have enough of them to give a base for the topology.

Having no linear functionals is highly undesirable for the purposes of doing analysis. In case of the Lebesgue measure on formula_312 rather than work with formula_11 for formula_282 it is common to work with the Hardy space whenever possible, as this has quite a few linear functionals: enough to distinguish points from one another. However, the Hahn–Banach theorem still fails in for formula_315 .

