In this theorem, which is due to Alexander Grothendieck, it is crucial that the vector space formula_460 be a subset of formula_18 since it is possible to construct an infinite-dimensional closed vector subspace of formula_492 (which is even a subset of formula_493), where formula_494 is Lebesgue measure on the unit circle formula_495 and formula_496 is the probability measure that results from dividing it by its mass formula_497

==Applications==

===Statistics===

In statistics, measures of central tendency and statistical dispersion, such as the mean, median, and standard deviation, can be defined in terms of formula_11 metrics, and measures of central tendency can be characterized as solutions to variational problems.

In penalized regression, &quot;L1 penalty&quot; and &quot;L2 penalty&quot; refer to penalizing either the formula_425 norm of a solution&#x27;s vector of parameter values (i.e. the sum of its absolute values), or its squared formula_270 norm (its Euclidean length). Techniques which use an L1 penalty, like LASSO, encourage sparse solutions (where the many parameters are zero). Elastic net regularization uses a penalty term that is a combination of the formula_425 norm and the squared formula_270 norm of the parameter vector.

===Hausdorff–Young inequality===

The Fourier transform for the real line (or, for periodic functions, see Fourier series), maps formula_503 to formula_504 (or formula_505 to formula_506) respectively, where formula_507 and formula_508 This is a consequence of the Riesz–Thorin interpolation theorem, and is made precise with the Hausdorff–Young inequality.

By contrast, if formula_509 the Fourier transform does not map into formula_510

===Hilbert spaces===
Hilbert spaces are central to many applications, from quantum mechanics to stochastic calculus. The spaces formula_270 and formula_269 are both Hilbert spaces. In fact, by choosing a Hilbert basis formula_513 i.e., a maximal orthonormal subset of formula_270 or any Hilbert space, one sees that every Hilbert space is isometrically isomorphic to formula_515 (same formula_516 as above), i.e., a Hilbert space of type formula_517

