=== spaces on manifolds===

One may also define spaces formula_582 on a manifold, called the intrinsic formula_11 spaces of the manifold, using densities.

===Vector-valued spaces===

Given a measure space formula_584 and a locally convex space formula_516 (here assumed to be complete), it is possible to define spaces of formula_8-integrable formula_516-valued functions on formula_588 in a number of ways. One way is to define the spaces of Bochner integrable and Pettis integrable functions, and then endow them with locally convex TVS-topologies that are (each in their own way) a natural generalization of the usual formula_11 topology. Another way involves topological tensor products of formula_590 with formula_591 Element of the vector space formula_592 are finite sums of simple tensors formula_593 where each simple tensor formula_594 may be identified with the function formula_595 that sends formula_596 This tensor product formula_592 is then endowed with a locally convex topology that turns it into a topological tensor product, the most common of which are the projective tensor product, denoted by formula_598 and the injective tensor product, denoted by formula_599 In general, neither of these space are complete so their completions are constructed, which are respectively denoted by formula_600 and formula_601 (this is analogous to how the space of scalar-valued simple functions on formula_602 when seminormed by any formula_220 is not complete so a completion is constructed which, after being quotiented by formula_604 is isometrically isomorphic to the Banach space formula_605). Alexander Grothendieck showed that when formula_516 is a nuclear space (a concept he introduced), then these two constructions are, respectively, canonically TVS-isomorphic with the spaces of Bochner and Pettis integral functions mentioned earlier; in short, they are indistinguishable.

=== space of measurable functions===

The vector space of (equivalence classes of) measurable functions on formula_90 is denoted formula_608 . By definition, it contains all the formula_609 and is equipped with the topology of &quot;convergence in measure&quot;. When formula_258 is a probability measure (i.e., formula_611), this mode of convergence is named &quot;convergence in probability&quot;. The space formula_612 is always a topological abelian group but is only a topological vector space if formula_613 This is because scalar multiplication is continuous if and only if formula_613 If formula_388 is formula_389-finite then the weaker topology of local convergence in measure is an F-space, i.e. a completely metrizable topological vector space. Moreover, this topology is isometric to global convergence in measure formula_617 for a suitable choice of probability measure formula_618

The description is easier when formula_258 is finite. If formula_258 is a finite measure on formula_621 the formula_117 function admits for the convergence in measure the following fundamental system of neighborhoods
