<doc id="45196" wikidata="Q182003" url="?curid=45196" title="Injective function">
<text>In mathematics, an injective function (also known as injection, or one-to-one function ) is a function that maps distinct elements of its domain to distinct elements of its codomain; that is, implies (equivalently by contraposition, implies ). In other words, every element of the function&#x27;s codomain is the image of one element of its domain. The term must not be confused with that refers to bijective functions, which are functions such that each element in the codomain is an image of exactly one element in the domain. 

A homomorphism between algebraic structures is a function that is compatible with the operations of the structures. For all common algebraic structures, and, in particular for vector spaces, an is also called a . However, in the more general context of category theory, the definition of a monomorphism differs from that of an injective homomorphism. This is thus a theorem that they are equivalent for algebraic structures; see for more details.

A function formula_1 that is not injective is sometimes called many-to-one.

== Definition ==
Let formula_1 be a function whose domain is a set formula_3 The function formula_1 is said to be injective provided that for all formula_5 and formula_6 in formula_7 if formula_8 then formula_9; that is, formula_10 implies formula_11 Equivalently, if formula_12 then formula_13 in the contrapositive statement.

Symbolically,formula_14
which is logically equivalent to the contrapositive,formula_15An injective function (or, more generally, a monomorphism) is often denoted by using the specialized arrows ↣ or ↪ (for example, formula_16 or formula_17), although some authors specifically reserve ↪ for an inclusion map. 

== Examples ==
&quot;For visual examples, readers are directed to the gallery section.&quot;
* For any set formula_18 and any subset formula_19 the inclusion map formula_20 (which sends any element formula_21 to itself) is injective. In particular, the identity function formula_22 is always injective (and in fact bijective).
* If the domain of a function is the empty set, then the function is the empty function, which is injective.
* If the domain of a function has one element (that is, it is a singleton set), then the function is always injective.
* The function formula_23 defined by formula_24 is injective.
* The function formula_25 defined by formula_26 is injective, because (for example) formula_27 However, if formula_28 is redefined so that its domain is the non-negative real numbers [0,+∞), then formula_28 is injective.
* The exponential function formula_30 defined by formula_31 is injective (but not surjective, as no real value maps to a negative number).
* The natural logarithm function formula_32 defined by formula_33 is injective.
* The function formula_25 defined by formula_35 is not injective, since, for example, formula_36

More generally, when formula_18 and formula_38 are both the real line formula_39 then an injective function formula_23 is one whose graph is never intersected by any horizontal line more than once. This principle is referred to as the .

== Injections can be undone ==

Functions with left inverses are always injections. That is, given formula_41 if there is a function formula_42 such that for every formula_43, formula_44, then formula_1 is injective. In this case, formula_28 is called a retraction of formula_47 Conversely, formula_1 is called a section of formula_49

Conversely, every injection formula_1 with a non-empty domain has a left inverse formula_28. It can be defined by choosing an element formula_5 in the domain of formula_1 and setting formula_54 to the unique element of the pre-image formula_55 (if it is non-empty) or to formula_5 (otherwise).

The left inverse formula_28 is not necessarily an inverse of formula_58 because the composition in the other order, formula_59 may differ from the identity on formula_60 In other words, an injective function can be &quot;reversed&quot; by a left inverse, but is not necessarily invertible, which requires that the function is bijective.

== Injections may be made invertible ==

In fact, to turn an injective function formula_61 into a bijective (hence invertible) function, it suffices to replace its codomain formula_38 by its actual image formula_63 That is, let formula_64 such that formula_65 for all formula_43; then formula_28 is bijective. Indeed, formula_1 can be factored as formula_69 where formula_70 is the inclusion function from formula_71 into formula_60

More generally, injective partial functions are called partial bijections.

== Other properties ==
* If formula_1 and formula_28 are both injective then formula_75 is injective.
* If formula_76 is injective, then formula_1 is injective (but formula_28 need not be).
* formula_61 is injective if and only if, given any functions formula_80 formula_81 whenever formula_82 then formula_83 In other words, injective functions are precisely the monomorphisms in the category Set of sets.
* If formula_61 is injective and formula_85 is a subset of formula_7 then formula_87 Thus, formula_85 can be recovered from its image formula_89
* If formula_61 is injective and formula_85 and formula_92 are both subsets of formula_7 then formula_94
* Every function formula_95 can be decomposed as formula_96 for a suitable injection formula_1 and surjection formula_49 This decomposition is unique up to isomorphism, and formula_1 may be thought of as the inclusion function of the range formula_100 of formula_101 as a subset of the codomain formula_38 of formula_103
* If formula_61 is an injective function, then formula_38 has at least as many elements as formula_7 in the sense of cardinal numbers. In particular, if, in addition, there is an injection from formula_38 to formula_7 then formula_18 and formula_38 have the same cardinal number. (This is known as the Cantor–Bernstein–Schroeder theorem.)
* If both formula_18 and formula_38 are finite with the same number of elements, then formula_61 is injective if and only if formula_1 is surjective (in which case formula_1 is bijective).
* An injective function which is a homomorphism between two algebraic structures is an embedding.
* Unlike surjectivity, which is a relation between the graph of a function and its codomain, injectivity is a property of the graph of the function alone; that is, whether a function formula_1 is injective can be decided by only considering the graph (and not the codomain) of formula_47

== Proving that functions are injective ==

A proof that a function formula_1 is injective depends on how the function is presented and what properties the function holds.
For functions that are given by some formula there is a basic idea.
We use the definition of injectivity, namely that if formula_119 then formula_120

Here is an example: 
formula_121

Proof: Let formula_122 Suppose formula_123 So formula_124 implies formula_125 which implies formula_120 Therefore, it follows from the definition that formula_1 is injective.

There are multiple other methods of proving that a function is injective. For example, in calculus if formula_1 is a differentiable function defined on some interval, then it is sufficient to show that the derivative is always positive or always negative on that interval. In linear algebra, if formula_1 is a linear transformation it is sufficient to show that the kernel of formula_1 contains only the zero vector. If formula_1 is a function with finite domain it is sufficient to look through the list of images of each domain element and check that no image occurs twice on the list.

A graphical approach for a real-valued function formula_1 of a real variable formula_133 is the horizontal line test. If every horizontal line intersects the curve of formula_134 in at most one point, then formula_1 is injective or one-to-one.

